of these structures to each other is understood, eg for femoral artery cannulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Starting laterally, which one of the following best describes the arrangement of structures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral nerve, femoral vein, femoral artery","Femoral vein, femoral nerve, femoral artery","Femoral artery, femoral nerve, femoral vein","Femoral nerve, femoral artery, femoral vein","Femoral artery, femoral vein, femoral nerve"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve, femoral artery, and femoral vein\u003C/strong\u003E are arranged in that order from lateral to medial within the femoral triangle. This arrangement can be remembered using the mnemonic \u0027NAVY\u0027 (Nerve, Artery, Vein, Y-lymphatics).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral nerve, femoral vein, femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This incorrectly places the vein between the nerve and artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral vein, femoral nerve, femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement is completely reversed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral artery, femoral nerve, femoral vein\u003C/strong\u003E - This incorrectly places the artery most laterally\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral artery, femoral vein, femoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement is completely reversed\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral triangle is bounded by the inguinal ligament superiorly, sartorius muscle laterally, and adductor longus muscle medially. Understanding this arrangement is crucial for clinical procedures such as femoral vessel cannulation and femoral nerve blocks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The femoral triangle contains the femoral nerve, femoral artery and femoral vein in a lateral-to-medial arrangement.","The boundaries of the femoral triangle are the inguinal ligament superiorly, sartorius laterally, and adductor longus medially.","The mnemonic \u0027NAVY\u0027 describes the contents from lateral to medial: Nerve, Artery, Vein, Y (lymphatics)"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cFemoral Triangle\u201d by Craig Hacking is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Femoral-triangle-diagram.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21324"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21324"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rd4DZRNNsNHiDZdFg3MAk5fyiwHxgH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rd4DZRNNsNHiDZdFg3MAk5fyiwHxgH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":671,"height":493}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T16:25:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T16:25:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10112"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112946"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap